To remove all nouns from a sentence in MATLAB, you'll need to use some natural language processing (NLP) techniques. Unfortunately, MATLAB doesn't have built-in support for advanced NLP like identifying parts of speech directly. However, you can make use of external libraries or toolboxes that offer NLP capabilities, such as the Stanford NLP toolbox.

Here's an example approach using MATLAB with an external NLP library:

1. Install the Stanford NLP toolbox or any other library that can perform part-of-speech tagging.
2. Use the library to tag each word in the sentence with its part of speech.
3. Filter out the nouns based on their POS tags.

Here's a pseudocode to give you an idea of how this might look:

```matlab
% Assuming you have a function that tags parts of speech
sentence = 'The cat jumped over the fence';
% Use an NLP library to tag parts of speech
posTagged = posTagger(sentence);

% posTagged might look like:
% {'The', 'DT'; 'cat', 'NN'; 'jumped', 'VBD'; 'over', 'IN'; 'the', 'DT'; 'fence', 'NN'}

% Initialize an empty cell array to hold words that are not nouns
filteredWords = {};

% Loop through each tagged word
for i = 1:size(posTagged, 1)
    word = posTagged{i, 1};
    pos = posTagged{i, 2};

    % Check if the POS tag is not a noun (NN, NNS, NNP, NNPS)
    if ~ismember(pos, {'NN', 'NNS', 'NNP', 'NNPS'})
        % Add the word to the filtered list
        filteredWords{end+1} = word;
    end
end

% Join the filtered words back into a sentence
filteredSentence = strjoin(filteredWords, ' ');

disp(filteredSentence);
```

Please note that this is a high-level overview and assumes the availability of a part-of-speech tagging function, which is typically provided by an NLP library. You'll need to set up the library and adapt the code accordingly to fit the library's API.

For a complete solution, you'll likely need to integrate MATLAB with Java or Python to use an NLP library like Stanford NLP or spaCy, which is more straightforward in Python. If you decide to use Python, you can leverage MATLAB's ability to call Python functions directly.
